---
import { Image } from "astro:assets";

import noelHeadshot from "@images/noel-headshot.jpg";
import Button from "@/components/button/Button.astro";
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About RRPN"
  description="The Responsible Recovery Planning Network produces best-practices policy research, advocacy, and education for communities recovering from disaster and building lasting resilience."
>
  <!-- Page header -->
  <section class="bg-primary-700">
    <div class="site-container pt-36 pb-16 md:pt-44 md:pb-20">
      <h1 class="h1 text-base-50 max-w-3xl">About RRPN</h1>
      <p class="text-primary-100 mt-4 max-w-2xl text-lg">
        Better planning for a resilient California.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Mission (full statement from approved brand package) -->
  <section class="site-container py-16 md:py-24" aria-label="Our mission">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <h2 class="h2 text-primary">Our mission</h2>
      <div class="mt-6 space-y-5 text-lg leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          When California communities face disaster and the long work of recovery, the policies that
          decide their future — wildfire and utility policy, disaster recovery, insurance, climate
          adaptation, housing, and land use — are increasingly tangled, and the communities affected
          are too often the last to be heard.
        </p>
        <p>
          The Responsible Recovery Planning Network exists to close that gap. We produce
          rigorous, best-practices policy research; we advocate for recovery and resilience policies
          that respect both statewide goals and community self-determination; and we educate residents,
          practitioners, and policymakers so that everyone at the table understands what the law
          says, what it means, and what it could be.
        </p>
        <p>
          RRPN operates as a portfolio of community projects. Our first, Altadena Recovery Watch,
          grew out of the 2025 Eaton Fire and now engages thousands of residents on the state
          legislation shaping their recovery and rebuilding.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- About Noel -->
  <section class="bg-base-100 border-y" aria-label="About the founder">
    <div class="site-container py-16 md:py-24">
      <div class="mx-auto grid max-w-5xl gap-12 lg:grid-cols-[minmax(0,300px)_1fr]">
        <div>
          <Image
            src={noelHeadshot}
            alt="Noel Hyun Minor, founder of the Responsible Recovery Planning Network"
            class="border-border w-full max-w-xs rounded-lg border shadow-sm"
            width={600}
          />
        </div>
        <div>
          <h2 class="h2 text-primary">About Noel</h2>
          <p class="text-muted-foreground mt-1 text-sm tracking-wide uppercase">
            Noel Hyun Minor &middot; Founder
          </p>
          <div class="mt-6 space-y-5 leading-relaxed">
            <p>
              Noel Hyun Minor founded the Responsible Recovery Planning Network to bring
              clarity and good judgment to how California plans, builds, and rebuilds. A native
              Angeleno, a former real estate, land-use, and environmental attorney, and a graduate
              of the USC Gould School of Law, Noel has spent her career at the intersection of
              housing, land use, and public policy — and, unusually, she has seen that intersection
              from nearly every side.
            </p>
            <p>
              That range is the point. Noel served as a staffer to former Los Angeles City
              Councilmember and Mayor Eric Garcetti, which gave her a firsthand view of how policy
              is actually made. As a land-use attorney at DLA Piper and Liner LLP, she advocated
              for business interests — securing entitlements for complex redevelopment projects and
              public-private partnerships, including work with LA Metro and community redevelopment
              agencies. As an advocate with the Central City Association, she championed the
              renaissance of downtown Los Angeles. She has served her own community directly, formerly serving on the
              Central Hollywood Neighborhood Council, as a Neighborhood Council Budget Advocate
              under Mayor Antonio Villaraigosa, and on the boards of charter schools and private
              schools. She is a landlord herself, with a direct stake in how housing rules land in
              practice, and has also served on the board of the West Hollywood Community Housing
              Corporation — a non-profit affordable housing developer. Few people in this space have
              stood in all of those places.
            </p>
            <p>
              Her particular strength is bringing those lenses together. Noel has seen how a single
              well-intentioned law reads to a City Hall staffer, a developer, a neighbor, and a
              property owner all at once — and she uses that whole-picture view to help shape policy
              that is sensible, durable, and grounded in how communities actually function.
            </p>
            <p>
              RRPN grew directly out of that instinct. When the January 2025 Eaton Fire swept
              through the Altadena area, Noel did not lose her own home — but many of her friends
              did, and the fire reshaped her family's daily life, from the loss of her son's school
              to the community club at the center of their weeks. As out-of-town speculators moved
              to use California's by-right density laws to subdivide fire-cleared lots before
              residents could return, Noel convened Altadena Recovery Watch — a network of residents
              and local organizations that helped inform SB 1090, the "Keep Altadena Land in
              Altadena Hands" Act, which passed out of both Assembly policy committees
              on July 1, 2026. It stands as one example of the approach RRPN is built to scale:
              resident-informed, fact-driven, and transparent.
            </p>
            <p>
              Today, RRPN carries that work statewide — not as a partisan or single-issue campaign,
              but as an organization focused on education and transparency in service of
              responsible, resilient recovery and planning. For Noel, this is not abstract policy. It is
              the region she comes from, and the communities she wants to see rebuild well.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Transparency -->
  <section class="site-container py-16 md:py-24" aria-label="Transparency">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <h2 class="h2 text-primary">Transparency</h2>
      <div class="mt-6 space-y-5 leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          RRPN is newly formed, and its legal formation is in progress. We believe organizations
          that ask for the public's trust should earn it in the open, and we're glad to answer
          questions about how RRPN is structured, governed, and funded.
        </p>
        <p>
          Questions about our structure, funding, or governance are welcome at
          <a
            class="text-terracotta-600 underline hover:no-underline"
            href="mailto:info@rrpn.org">info@rrpn.org</a
          >.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-10">
        <Button href="/get-involved" variant="primary" arrow="right">Get involved</Button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
